The paper deals with the development of machine learning models that can operate under different levels of automation, which is a problem that falls under the category of machine learning (cs.LG) and artificial intelligence (cs.AI). The paper also introduces a new representation of the objective function that is based on submodularity, which is a concept that is commonly used in the field of data science (cs.DS) and optimization (cs.CE). Finally, the paper presents experiments on two real-world applications that involve human decision-making, which suggests that the paper may also be relevant to the field of human-computer interaction (cs.HC).
